Here's the complete migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | Wait before force-kill | `Thread.Join(timeout)` |
| `GetNextItem()` (may block) | Blocking call interruption | Must accept `CancellationToken` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking unblocks
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — just continue to let finally run
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time — log a warning.
            // In modern .NET there is NO way to force-kill a managed thread.
            // If this fires, GetNextItem or ProcessItem needs better
            // cancellation token support.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept and respect the token.** If it blocks on I/O, a queue, or `Thread.Sleep`, cancellation won't take effect until it returns. Example fix:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) — blocks indefinitely
private Item GetNextItem() => _queue.Take();

// After (.NET 8) — wakes immediately on cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) => _queue.Take(token);
// BlockingCollection<T>.Take(CancellationToken) throws
// OperationCanceledException when the token fires.
```

**2. You cannot force-stop an uncooperative thread.** `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8. If the thread ignores the token, your only option is to move the work to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()`.

**3. `Thread.ResetAbort()` has no equivalent** — it's simply not needed. With cooperative cancellation, no exception is injected; you check `IsCancellationRequested` and decide whether to continue or exit.

**4. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` silently** in library code. The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter above ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one.

**5. Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It's `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. That's why `IDisposable` was added to the class.

**6. Replace `Thread.Sleep` with token-aware waits** anywhere else in the codebase:

```csharp
// Before
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// After — wakes immediately on cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);
```

## Validation Checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort` references remain
- ✅ No `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks remain
- ✅ No `Thread.ResetAbort` calls remain
- ✅ All cancellable work accepts `CancellationToken`
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed
- ✅ Builds cleanly on `net8.0` with zero `SYSLIB0006` warnings
